│ THOUGHT                                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ The root of the problem is a disagreement between LLVM's legacy vectorization cost model and the new VPlan-based cost model. The VPlan model correctly identifies that a first-order     │
│ recurrence in the provided test case is dead code and can be eliminated. This optimization leads to a lower cost estimate. The legacy model does not perform this analysis, resulting in │
│ a higher cost. The assertion `VPlan cost model and legacy cost model disagreed` fires because the function `planContainsAdditionalSimplifications`, which is meant to account for such   │
│ valid discrepancies, does not check for the elimination of dead recurrences.                                                                                                             │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ To fix this, I will modify the `planContainsAdditionalSimplifications` function in `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp`. The correct logic is to iterate through all the    │
│ recipes in the VPlan and check if any `VPFirstOrderRecurrencePHIRecipe` is not live (i.e., its `isLive()` method returns `false`). A non-live recipe indicates that the recurrence it    │
│ represents has been optimized away by VPlan. If such a recipe is found, the function should return `true`, signaling that a valid simplification has occurred and preventing the         │
│ assertion failure.                                                                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The previous attempts to solve this issue were plagued by a corrupted source file due to incorrect `sed` commands. To ensure a clean and correct patch, I will use a precise `sed`       │
│ command that targets the exact line range of the original function and replaces it entirely with the new, correct implementation. This is the most robust method available in this       │
│ environment.                                                                                                                                                                             │
